The paper deals with the traveling salesman problem, which is a classic problem in computer science and optimization. The paper presents a new family of instances where the nearest neighbor rule performs poorly, which is relevant to the field of approximation algorithms (cs.DS). The instances are defined in terms of different metrics, including the euclidean and rectilinear metrics, which suggests that the paper may be relevant to computational geometry (cs.CG). The paper also presents lower bounds on the performance of the nearest neighbor rule, which is related to the field of discrete mathematics (cs.DM). The paper may also be relevant to the field of network optimization (cs.NE) and game theory (cs.GT), as the traveling salesman problem has applications in these areas.
